snippet.textDisplay:
To whom it may concern, Apple does not track you across third-party apps and websites.
All the warning asks is that users give consent for apps to track them across third party (other developers') apps and websites. So the warning only applies to apps which behave strictly more invasively than Apple does. App developers do not have to ask user consent to be tracked inside their own apps, but Apple does a pretty good job of warning users when they track you inside Apple apps also, holding themselves to a higher standard than that to which they hold developers on their platform. Does anyone actually informed about this see it differently? Because Rene Ritchie has already debunked this one over and over.

So in answer to your somewhat joking question, Riley, if you use iPhone and Safari with an internet provider other than T-Mobile, you don't get tracked across apps and websites by Apple, or Google, or T-Mobile, but likely by whoever your internet provider is unless you use a VPN. I use Private Internet Access. You heard of it?

I am alarmed when this show talks about Apple and privacy and lumps Apple in with companies whose business model it is to track you without your knowledge. Apple makes their money when you pay for their products and services. They've continually pushed for better privacy practices across the industry, and this show, along with the rest of YouTube, would do well to recognize that. Contributing to misinformation about privacy, even through jest, is beneath you all.
